​Arduino UNO Pin Types & IoT Use Cases


​1. Digital Input
​Explanation: These pins read strict binary signals—either a 1 (HIGH / 5V) or a 0 (LOW / 0V). They are used to detect simple "on/off" or "yes/no" states.
​Arduino UNO Pins: Pins 0 to 13.
​Real IoT Use Case: Reading a PIR motion sensor. If the sensor detects movement (HIGH), the IoT system triggers an alert on a smart home security app.
​

2. Digital Output
​Explanation: These pins send out strict binary signals (5V for HIGH, 0V for LOW) to control connected components.
​Arduino UNO Pins: Pins 0 to 13.
​Real IoT Use Case: Sending a HIGH signal to a relay module that turns on a physical water pump in an automated smart agriculture system.
​

3. Analog Input
​Explanation: analog pins can read a continuous range of voltages between 0V and 5V. The internal Analog-to-Digital Converter (ADC) translates this voltage into a number between 0 and 1023.
​Arduino UNO Pins: Pins A0 to A5.
​Real IoT Use Case: Reading a soil moisture sensor. Instead of just "wet" or "dry," the sensor provides an exact moisture percentage so the system knows exactly how much water the crops need.
​

4. PWM Output (Pulse Width Modulation)
​Explanation: PWM pins are digital pins that can rapidly flip on and off to simulate an analog output (like sending 2.5V instead of just 0V or 5V).
​Arduino UNO Pins: Pins 3, 5, 6, 9, 10, and 11 (marked with a squiggly line ~ on the board).
​Real IoT Use Case: Controlling the exact speed of a DC motor in a smart ventilation fan, or smoothly dimming a smart LED bulb based on the time of day.
​

5. I2C / SPI Pins (Communication)
​Explanation: These are specialized pins used for advanced, high-speed communication between the Arduino and complex sensors, displays, or other microcontrollers.
​Arduino UNO Pins: * I2C: A4 (SDA - Data) and A5 (SCL - Clock).
​SPI: 10 (SS), 11 (MOSI), 12 (MISO), and 13 (SCK).
​Real IoT Use Case: Connecting a high-precision BME280 weather sensor (which measures temperature, humidity, and barometric pressure all at once) to an IoT weather station using the I2C pins.
